ta: Entities (174, 1357); Relationships (1907)]\"},{\"summary\":\"The community’s practical work is built around demonstrating CO₂ release from respiration\",\"explanation\":\"A central experimental thread is the “Demonstration of the products of respiration,” described as a classroom apparatus (with labeled vessels and reagents) that shows carbon dioxide is released during respiration, evidenced by limewater turning milky after CO₂ is produced by the organism in the setup. [Data: Entities (1270, 1280, 1231); Relationships (1799, 1754)]\\n\\nThe frog is explicitly identified as the respiring organism placed in the apparatus to release CO₂, linking the organism to the observable indicator outcome (limewater’s milky change) and making the conceptual product (CO₂) experimentally detectable. [Data: Entities (1095, 1270); Relationships (1798, 1799)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Limewater/Lime water functions as the visible CO₂ indicator that anchors interpretation of results\",\"explanation\":\"Limewater is described as an indicator solution used in these respiration experiments; its change is used to infer the presence of carbon dioxide in airflow. In the demonstration context, “lime water” specifically is noted to turn milky in the presence of CO₂, providing a direct visual readout for CO₂ production from respiration. [Data: Entities (1231, 1280, 1270); Relationships (1754, 1799)]\\n\\nThe relationships explicitly connect limewater to carbon dioxide and to the demonstration itself, indicating that the community’s experimental logic depends on a chemical indicator-response mapping (CO₂ → limewater turns milky) to support the instructional claim that respiration releases CO₂. [Data: Relationships (1754, 1799)]\"},{\"summary\":\"KOH is the chemical control element used to absorb CO₂ so oxygen uptake can be observed\",\"explanation\":\"KOH (potassium hydroxide) is described as a chemical absorbent for carbon dioxide in respiration apparatus. By removing CO₂ from the air entering the 